  "eprint": {
    "title": "DANA - Universal Dataflow Analysis for Gate-Level Netlist Reverse Engineering",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Nils Albartus",
        "email": "hoffmann@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Max Hoffmann",
        "email": "albartus@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Sebastian Temme",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Leonid Azriel",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Christof Paar",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Reverse engineering of integrated circuits, i.e., understanding the internals\nof IC, is required for many benign and malicious applications. Examples of the\nformer are detection of patent infringements, hardware Trojans or IP-theft, as\nwell as interface recovery and defect analysis, while malicious applications\ninclude IP-theft and finding insertion points for hardware Trojans. However,\nregardless of the application, the reverse engineer initially starts with a\nlarge unstructured netlist, forming an incomprehensible sea of gates.\n\nThis work presents DANA, a generic, technology-agnostic, and fully automated\ndataflow analysis methodology for flattened gate-level netlists. By analyzing\nthe flow of data between individual FF, DANA recovers high-level registers.\nThe key idea behind DANA is to combine independent metrics based on structural\nand control information with a powerful automated architecture. Notably, DANA\nworks without any thresholds, scenario-dependent parameters, or other \"magic\"\nvalues that the user must choose. We evaluate DANA on nine modern hardware\ndesigns, ranging from cryptographic co-processors, over CPUs, to the\nOpenTitan, a state-of-the-art SOC, which is maintained by the lowRISC\ninitiative with supporting industry partners like Google and Western Digital.\nOur results demonstrate almost perfect recovery of registers for all case\nstudies, regardless whether they were synthesized as FPGA or ASIC netlists.\nFurthermore, we explore two applications for dataflow analysis: we show that\nthe raw output of DANA often already allows to identify crucial components and\nhigh-level architecture features and also demonstrate its applicability for\ndetecting simple hardware Trojans.\n\nHence, DANA can be applied universally as the first step when investigating\nunknown netlists and provides major guidance for human analysts by structuring\nand condensing the otherwise incomprehensible sea of gates.\nOur implementation of DANA and all synthesized netlists are available as open\nsource on GitHub.",
    "keywords": [
      "Hardware Reverse Engineering",
      "Gate Level Netlists",
      "Dataflow Analysis"
    ],
    "category": "Applications",
